      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It's not just loud talkers, it's talkers period (Coping: "Loud Talkers, the Scourge of the Earth," May 19). I've seen my favorite entertainments succumb to  this one by one.</p>
        <p>In the 1940's, people sat in the movies in a reverential hush. Now they talk as if they were in their living room, because of television. The last bastion is the Museum of Modern Art. And then the theater. When I saw "Cats" a dozen years ago, I turned to the man behind me when I could stand it no more, and told him to stop yakking. "But I was speaking to my wife," he replied, as if that made it all right.</p>
        <p>A week ago I was bothered by the subscriber who sits behind me at the Philharmonic. I will have different seats next season (not because of this), but I would have reminded him firmly, but tactfully, of his bad concert manners.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL DESKEY Upper East Side</p>
      </block>
